Advanced Functional Ecology

Responses of Canopy-Inhabiting Beetle Communities to Eucalyptus Dieback Across Environmental Gradients in Kosciuszko National Park

Maha Yudha Samawi

2025-12-06

This R Markdown document presents the data analysis workflow for the beetle project. It begins by importing and preparing the beetle and environmental datasets, then uses species accumulation curves to assess sampling completeness and richness patterns. Next, it applies Kruskall-Wallis and PERMANOVA to test differences in abundance, richness, and community composition across dieback conditions or sites. In the last part, redundancy analysis (RDA) is used to identify key environmental variables shaping beetle assemblages and to visualise patterns in multivariate community structure.

Import Data

For this project, two different input datasets are used. The first dataset contains the abundance of each species and is hereafter referred to as abd. The second dataset is a compilation of species composition per tree together with the associated environmental variables for each tree, and is referred to as data.

The abd dataset contains the abundance of all species for each category. Therefore, it includes zero values. Because iNEXT does not accept zero counts, each column was defined separately and zero values were removed prior to analysis (1: piper, 2: Sponars Chalet). The data were then grouped again, and species accumulation curves were modelled.

# define each column
plot1_abund    <- abd$Plot_1
plot2_abund <- abd$Plot_2

#remove species with 0 abundance in each column
plot1_abund    <- plot1_abund[plot1_abund > 0]
plot2_abund <- plot2_abund[plot2_abund > 0]

# build assemblage list
comm_list <- list(
  Piper    = plot1_abund,
  Sponars_Chalet = plot2_abund
)

# run iNEXT
out <- iNEXT(comm_list, q=c(0,1,2), datatype="abundance", size=NULL, endpoint=NULL, knots=40, se=TRUE, conf=0.95,nboot=50)

#Visualization
ggiNEXT(out, type=1, facet.var="Order.q", color.var="Assemblage")

# Calculate species richness (number of species present per tree)
data$Richness <- rowSums(species > 0, na.rm = TRUE)

# Calculate total abundance (sum of all individuals per tree)
data$TotalAbundance <- rowSums(species, na.rm = TRUE)

# Verify calculations

# Function to create richness and abundance plots
create_richness_abundance_plots <- function(data, var_name, var_label) {
  
  # Check if variable is categorical or continuous
  is_cat <- is.factor(data[[var_name]]) | is.character(data[[var_name]]) | 
    length(unique(data[[var_name]])) <= 5
  
  if(is_cat) {
    # Categorical variable - boxplot
    p_richness <- ggplot(data, aes(x = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]), y = Richness, 
                                   fill = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]))) +
      geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5) +
      labs(x = var_label, y = "Species Richness") +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(legend.position = "none",
            axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
    
    p_abundance <- ggplot(data, aes(x = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]), y = TotalAbundance, 
                                    fill = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]))) +
      geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5) +
      labs(x = var_label, y = "Total Abundance") +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(legend.position = "none",
            axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
    
  } else {
    # Continuous variable - scatter plot
    p_richness <- ggplot(data, aes(x = .data[[var_name]], y = Richness)) +
      geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 1.5) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "darkgreen") +
      labs(title = paste("Richness -", var_label),
           x = var_label, y = "Species Richness") +
      theme_minimal()
    
    p_abundance <- ggplot(data, aes(x = .data[[var_name]], y = TotalAbundance)) +
      geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 1.5) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "purple") +
      labs(title = paste("Abundance -", var_label),
           x = var_label, y = "Total Abundance") +
      theme_minimal()
  }
  
  return(list(richness = p_richness, abundance = p_abundance))
}

# Create individual plots for each variable
rich_abund_cnp <- create_richness_abundance_plots(data, "Cnp", "Dieback")
rich_abund_bark <- create_richness_abundance_plots(data, "Bark", "Bark")
rich_abund_epi <- create_richness_abundance_plots(data, "Epi", "Epi")

# All Richness plots together
all_richness <- rich_abund_cnp$richness + rich_abund_bark$richness + rich_abund_epi$richness +
  plot_layout(ncol = 3)

# All Abundance plots together  
all_abundance <- rich_abund_cnp$abundance + rich_abund_bark$abundance + rich_abund_epi$abundance + 
  plot_layout(ncol = 3)

# Create a long format dataframe for faceting
diversity_long <- data %>%
  select(Shannon, Simpson, Cnp, Bark, Epi) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Cnp, Bark, Epi),
               names_to = "Variable",
               values_to = "Value") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Shannon, Simpson),
               names_to = "Index",
               values_to = "Diversity")


# Function to create individual diversity plots
create_diversity_plot <- function(data, var_name, var_label) {
  
  # Check if variable is categorical or continuous
  is_cat <- is.factor(data[[var_name]]) | is.character(data[[var_name]]) | 
    length(unique(data[[var_name]])) <= 5
  
  if(is_cat) {
    # Categorical variable - boxplot
    p_shannon <- ggplot(data, aes(x = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]), y = Shannon, 
                                  fill = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]))) +
      geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5) +
      labs(x = var_label, y = "Shannon Index") +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(legend.position = "none",
            axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
    
    p_simpson <- ggplot(data, aes(x = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]), y = Simpson, 
                                  fill = as.factor(.data[[var_name]]))) +
      geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5) +
      labs(x = var_label, y = "Simpson Index") +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(legend.position = "none",
            axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
    
  } else {
    # Continuous variable - scatter plot
    p_shannon <- ggplot(data, aes(x = .data[[var_name]], y = Shannon)) +
      geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 1.5) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "blue") +
      labs(title = paste("Shannon -", var_label),
           x = var_label, y = "Shannon Index") +
      theme_minimal()
    
    p_simpson <- ggplot(data, aes(x = .data[[var_name]], y = Simpson)) +
      geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 1.5) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "red") +
      labs(title = paste("Simpson -", var_label),
           x = var_label, y = "Simpson Index") +
      theme_minimal()
  }
  
  return(list(shannon = p_shannon, simpson = p_simpson))
}

# Create individual plots for each variable
plots_cnp <- create_diversity_plot(data, "Cnp", "Dieback")
plots_bark <- create_diversity_plot(data, "Bark", "Bark")
plots_epi <- create_diversity_plot(data, "Epi", "Epichromic Branch")


# All Shannon plots together
all_shannon <- plots_cnp$shannon + plots_bark$shannon + plots_epi$shannon +
  plot_layout(ncol = 3)
# All Simpson plots together  
all_simpson <- plots_cnp$simpson + plots_bark$simpson + plots_epi$simpson +
  plot_layout(ncol = 3) 

# Display
all_shannon

all_simpson

Kruskal-Wallis and PERMANOVA Test

I first conducted KruskalWallis tests to compare total abundance and total species richness across dieback conditions. I then examined differences in species composition using PERMANOVA. For this analysis, I used the data dataset but separated it into two components: (1) an env table containing environmental variables, and (2) a species matrix representing species composition. Because some dieback stands had no beetle records, I removed empty rows prior to analysis. I then calculated BrayCurtis ecological distances and ran PERMANOVA using the adonis function in the vegan package to evaluate how species composition varied with dieback condition.

library(vegan)

data <- read.csv("F:/Course/Kosi/RUN/all.csv",sep=";")
data$Bark <- as.factor(data$Bark)
data$Cnp <- as.factor(data$Cnp)
data$Epi <- as.factor(data$Epi)
data$D_Mean <- as.factor(data$D_Mean)


#Kruskal-Wallis test
kruskal.test(Abd~Cnp,data = data)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  Abd by Cnp
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 18.673, df = 1, p-value = 1.551e-05
kruskal.test(Abd~Bark,data = data)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  Abd by Bark
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 3.7017, df = 2, p-value = 0.1571
kruskal.test(Abd~Epi,data = data)

##  $ Epi   : Factor w/ 2 levels "1","2": 1 1 2 1 2 1 2 2 2 1 ...
##  $ D_Mean: Factor w/ 5 levels "1","2","3","4",..: 2 3 3 2 2 2 4 3 3 3 ...
env$Elev.<- as.numeric(env$Elev.)
env$Bark <- as.factor(env$Bark)
env$Cnp <- as.factor(env$Cnp)
env$Epi <- as.factor(env$Epi)
env$D_Mean <- as.factor(env$D_Mean)

# Remove empty rows (trees with no species)
empty_rows <- which(rowSums(species) == 0)
if(length(empty_rows) > 0) {
  species <- species[-empty_rows, ]
  env <- env[-empty_rows, ]
}

# Verify they match
cat("Row names match:", data(rownames(species) == rownames(env)), "\n")
## Warning in data(rownames(species) == rownames(env)): data set
## 'rownames(species) == rownames(env)' not found
## Row names match: rownames(species) == rownames(env)
cat("Same number of rows:", nrow(species) == nrow(env), "\n")
## Same number of rows: TRUE
# Calculate distance matrix
dist_species <- vegdist(species, method = "bray")

#Permanova
adonis2(dist_species~Cnp,data = env,permutations = 9999)

RDA Analysis

I transformed the species composition matrix (species) using a Hellinger transformation before performing RDA. To identify the best explanatory model, I applied stepwise model selection using ordistep. I first fitted a full RDA model that included all environmental variables, then used both forward and backward selection to determine the most parsimonious model. The final selected model was subsequently visualised.

# Hellinger transformation of species data (recommended for RDA with count data)
species_hell <- decostand(species, method = "hellinger")

# Perform initial RDA with all environmental variables
rda_full <- rda(species_hell ~ ., data = env)
summary(rda_full)

# Forward and Backward selection
rda_both <- ordistep(rda(species_hell ~ 1, data = env),
                     scope = formula(rda_full),
                     direction = "both",
                     permutations = 9999)
